---
import CalculatorPage from "../../components/CalculatorPage.astro";
import BudgetCalc from "../../components/calculators/BudgetCalc.tsx";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is the 50/30/20 rule?",
    a: "It's a simple budgeting framework: spend about 50% of your take-home pay on needs, 30% on wants, and put 20% toward savings and debt payoff. It's popular because it's easy to remember and flexible.",
  },
  {
    q: "What counts as a need vs a want?",
    a: "Needs are essentials you can't easily skip: rent or mortgage, groceries, utilities, transport, insurance, and minimum debt payments. Wants are everything else — dining out, streaming, travel, hobbies, and upgrades.",
  },
  {
    q: "What if my needs are more than 50%?",
    a: "That's common in high-cost areas. Use the sliders to set a realistic split for your situation — maybe 60/20/20. The rule is a guideline, not a law. The goal is simply to keep some money flowing to savings every month.",
  },
  {
    q: "Should the 20% go to savings or debt?",
    a: "Both. If you have high-interest debt, prioritize it within the 20% bucket, while keeping a small emergency fund. Once the expensive debt is gone, redirect the full 20% to savings and investing.",
  },
];
---

<CalculatorPage
  slug="budget"
  heading="50/30/20 Budget Calculator"
  intro="Enter your monthly take-home pay and instantly see how much to spend on needs and wants, and how much to save — using the simple 50/30/20 rule."
  placement="budget"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <BudgetCalc slot="calculator" client:load />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <h2>Budgeting without the spreadsheet</h2>
    <p>
      The 50/30/20 rule is the easiest budget to actually stick to. Instead of
      tracking dozens of categories, you split your take-home pay into just three
      buckets: needs, wants, and savings. It gives you guardrails without
      micromanaging every coffee.
    </p>

    <h2>The three buckets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>50% Needs</strong> — rent or mortgage, groceries, utilities, transport, insurance, and minimum debt payments.</li>
      <li><strong>30% Wants</strong> — dining out, subscriptions, travel, hobbies, and the nice-to-haves that make life enjoyable.</li>
      <li><strong>20% Savings</strong> — emergency fund, retirement, investments, and extra payments on debt.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Make it fit your life</h2>
    <p>
      If you live somewhere expensive, your needs might genuinely run higher than
      50%. That's fine — adjust the sliders to a split you can sustain. What matters
      most is that the savings bucket never hits zero. Even 10% saved consistently
      beats a perfect budget you abandon after a month.
    </p>

    <h2>Pay yourself first</h2>
    <p>
      Once you know your savings number, automate it. Schedule the transfer for the
      day you're paid so the money is gone before you can spend it. Budgeting works
      best when the right choice is the automatic one.
    </p>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorPage>
